WEBVTT

00:02.336 --> 00:05.840
ABRAHAM: For centuries,
mankind has been the dominant species.

00:06.215 --> 00:10.595
We've domesticated animals,
locked them up, killed them for sport.

00:10.761 --> 00:13.640
But a series of recent
events seem to suggest

00:13.805 --> 00:18.436
all across the globe animals
have decided "no more."

00:18.602 --> 00:20.229
And so we were hired,

00:20.395 --> 00:22.489
a team of people from
different backgrounds,

00:22.648 --> 00:24.116
with different specialties.

00:24.274 --> 00:26.618
An expert in animal behavior,

00:26.777 --> 00:28.154
a journalist,

00:28.320 --> 00:29.913
safari guide,

00:30.072 --> 00:31.699
foreign intelligence agent,

00:31.865 --> 00:33.788
and a veterinary pathologist.

00:33.951 --> 00:37.455
Our task: to Hnd out what is
happening with the animals,

00:37.621 --> 00:41.626
why it's happening,
and how to stop it.

00:43.126 --> 00:44.469
NARRATOR: Previously on Zoo:

00:44.628 --> 00:48.849
The Mother Cell is in every
single product Reiden makes.

00:49.341 --> 00:50.638
It's everywhere.

00:50.801 --> 00:53.725
It's all over the world
and it can't be stopped.

00:54.179 --> 00:57.103
- Where's your husband?
- Oh, my husband is back in Paris.

00:57.266 --> 00:58.984
Although he never
became my husband.

00:59.142 --> 01:01.691
I learned he was having
an affair with my sister.

01:02.312 --> 01:04.030
You're talking
about your daughter.

01:04.188 --> 01:05.907
Her name is Clementine,
she's 10 years old,

01:06.066 --> 01:07.568
she was diagnosed
three years ago.

01:08.151 --> 01:09.744
Why aren't you with her?

01:10.112 --> 01:11.489
I've waited too long.

01:12.155 --> 01:14.123
Uh, Jackson, hey.
Now's not really a good time.

01:14.283 --> 01:16.581
Jamie, listen to me.
Ben killed the optometrist.

01:16.827 --> 01:18.295
He isn't FBI.

01:18.453 --> 01:19.670
I don't wanna hurt you.

01:19.830 --> 01:21.582
Just give me the Mother Cell.

01:21.748 --> 01:23.170
[GRUNTING]

01:28.380 --> 01:30.553
Okay. That happened.

01:35.262 --> 01:37.811
[GRovvl_lNG]

01:53.363 --> 01:54.580
[GROWLING CONTINUES]

02:19.598 --> 02:20.645
[sNARl_lNG]

02:20.807 --> 02:22.024
What is that?

02:23.685 --> 02:25.187
The bears.

02:29.816 --> 02:30.863
[CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING]

02:31.026 --> 02:33.324
Oh, wait, I'm sorry. I.

02:33.487 --> 02:35.330
No, no, no. I'm just.

02:37.032 --> 02:40.081
- Hey, uh, I wasn't ready.
- We're good.

02:40.661 --> 02:42.504
I have everything I need.

02:47.417 --> 02:48.794
I should just turn myself in.

02:48.960 --> 02:50.758
I know. You said that.

02:50.921 --> 02:54.016
Just drink the iced tea.
It will make you feel better.

02:54.675 --> 02:57.269
JAMIE: Look, seriously, I...

02:57.761 --> 03:00.731
I shot a man, an FBI agent.

03:00.889 --> 03:02.983
I can't just walk
away from that.

03:03.141 --> 03:07.487
No, a man claiming to be an
FBI agent tried to kill you

03:07.646 --> 03:09.023
and you defended yourself.

03:09.189 --> 03:11.817
Quite capably, as Jackson says.

03:11.983 --> 03:13.451
But we can't prove that.

03:13.610 --> 03:15.112
So let's do something about it.

03:15.278 --> 03:19.909
Let's prove that not-really-FBI-Agent
Ben Shafer was working for Reiden.

03:20.075 --> 03:21.577
- Instead of ABRAHAM: We will.

03:23.537 --> 03:25.505
- We Will? ABRAHAM: Yes.

03:25.664 --> 03:28.133
- How?
- That I don't know yet.

03:28.291 --> 03:29.884
But we'll figure something out.

03:30.043 --> 03:34.344
Right now we worry about
keeping you safe, okay?

03:35.382 --> 03:37.100
Forty-eight hours?

03:37.259 --> 03:39.227
You said you could do it in two.

03:39.386 --> 03:41.184
I did, and I can.

03:41.346 --> 03:43.019
But only for repeat clientele.

03:44.808 --> 03:48.028
Consider us old friends
and make it an hour.

03:50.063 --> 03:51.485
I need a name.

03:52.607 --> 03:54.701
For the passport.

03:54.860 --> 03:56.453
Um...

03:56.653 --> 03:59.577
Armstrong. Nancy Armstrong.

04:16.298 --> 04:17.345
What are you thinking?

04:18.759 --> 04:21.478
It's attractive,
that's for sure.

04:23.180 --> 04:26.024
I'm also thinking there's no way
we can take this to the government.

04:26.183 --> 04:27.480
Not yet.

04:27.642 --> 04:28.814
Let's assume for a second

04:28.977 --> 04:31.150
that everything that the
chemist said was true.

04:31.313 --> 04:33.407
That molecules from
this Mother Cell are in

04:33.565 --> 04:35.408
every single one of
Reiden's products.

04:35.567 --> 04:36.739
We still need proof

04:36.902 --> 04:39.746
that this is what's causing the
aberrant behavior in the animals.

04:39.905 --> 04:41.532
We need, uh...

04:42.032 --> 04:46.333
I don't want to say a smoking
gun, that's way too dramatic,

04:46.495 --> 04:47.667
but a bloody knife?

04:48.121 --> 04:53.002
If we had a bloody knife,
then perhaps we could build a proper case.

04:53.460 --> 04:55.508
We're going to Paris.

04:57.380 --> 05:00.304
Not that I don't love that
sentence, but why? What's in Paris?

05:00.467 --> 05:02.970
A pack of four Eurasian brown
bears were being studied

05:03.136 --> 05:04.809
for migration and
feeding habits.

05:05.096 --> 05:07.269
Two days ago,
their trackers went offline.

05:07.432 --> 05:10.811
The bio-lab assumed it was just
interference with the satellite.

05:10.977 --> 05:13.355
Then, yesterday,
one of the bears showed up

05:13.522 --> 05:15.524
in an apartment in the
16th arrondissement

05:15.690 --> 05:17.410
and nearly killed the
woman who lived there.

05:18.235 --> 05:21.489
That bear is now apparently deep in
hibernation in a research facility.

05:21.655 --> 05:23.999
Um, hibernating?

05:24.157 --> 05:25.955
- In the middle of summer?
- Yes.

05:26.117 --> 05:28.165
And the rest of the
pack are still missing.

05:28.328 --> 05:30.171
MITCH: Sleuth. - Pardon?

05:31.456 --> 05:34.335
- A pack of bears is called a sleuth.
- Whatever. There.

05:34.501 --> 05:37.300
- There's your bloody knife.
- Yeah, well,

05:37.462 --> 05:41.592
if there's evidence of this Mother
Cell in that bear's bloodstream, then,

05:41.758 --> 05:42.805
that would do it.

05:42.968 --> 05:44.185
Perfect. When do we leave?

05:44.594 --> 05:46.517
CHLOE: Jamie's passport
will be ready in an hour.

05:46.680 --> 05:48.523
We'll have just enough
time to make our flight.

05:48.682 --> 05:50.400
Where are you going?

05:51.351 --> 05:52.648
Drugstore.

05:52.811 --> 05:56.281
If we're getting on a red-eye to
Paris, I need some melatonin.

05:58.108 --> 05:59.405
MAN: Yes, I understand.

05:59.568 --> 06:01.445
Will he know who you are?

06:01.611 --> 06:04.535
Okay, no, no, no.
I'm getting him now.

06:06.074 --> 06:07.667
You've forgotten how to knock?

06:07.826 --> 06:09.954
Have you heard of something
called the Mother Cell?

06:14.499 --> 06:17.628
- The Mother Cell? What's that?
- I don't know.

06:17.794 --> 06:20.718
But someone wants to talk to you.
He says that he has the Mother Cell

06:20.881 --> 06:23.521
and he's willing to give it back,
but he needs something in return.

06:25.510 --> 06:26.932
Transfer it.

06:27.345 --> 06:28.392
[PHONE RINGs]

06:28.555 --> 06:29.602
[WHISPERS] Go.

06:31.308 --> 06:32.355
[PHONE BEEPS]

06:33.310 --> 06:34.402
[IN NORMAL VOICE] Hello?

06:35.145 --> 06:36.772
Hello.

06:37.397 --> 06:39.115
Uh, you don't know me,

06:39.274 --> 06:42.619
but you're gonna want to listen very
carefully to what I have to say.

07:20.857 --> 07:23.781
How do we tell if he's been
infected by the Mother Cell?

07:23.944 --> 07:26.993
Grab me that tray of test
tubes over there, will you?

07:27.530 --> 07:29.578
I'm gonna take a blood panel

07:29.741 --> 07:32.369
and hope that some
foreign elements show up.

07:32.535 --> 07:33.582
If they do,

07:33.745 --> 07:36.624
I'll compare their chemical
structure with the Mother Cell.

07:36.790 --> 07:38.792
And if they match,

07:39.376 --> 07:40.628
we've got our answer.

07:40.794 --> 07:43.673
So, basically,
you're looking for a fingerprint,

07:43.838 --> 07:46.387
- chemically speaking.
MITCH: Look at you.

07:46.758 --> 07:47.884
Getting all science-y.

07:48.969 --> 07:52.223
Ten drops each,
in each of those test tubes.

07:52.389 --> 07:55.188
And as a backup,
we'll take a DNA sample.

07:55.350 --> 07:56.476
Takes a little longer,

07:56.643 --> 07:58.520
but might as well while we're
here, right?

07:58.687 --> 08:01.236
Would you mind taking a swab
from our friend's mouth there?

08:01.398 --> 08:02.900
[BEAR sNoRING]

08:03.066 --> 08:04.693
Sure.

08:07.779 --> 08:09.372
[MONITOR BEEPING]

08:09.531 --> 08:11.704
- He's waking up.
- Oh, that's okay.

08:12.242 --> 08:14.244
- Says you.
- No, really. It's fine.

08:14.411 --> 08:15.503
Even in hibernation,

08:15.662 --> 08:18.381
a bear's heart rate increases
when a predator approaches.

08:18.540 --> 08:20.338
It's nature's little
warning signal.

08:20.500 --> 08:23.003
Apparently,
you're quite predatory.

08:23.169 --> 08:24.762
Okay.

08:30.552 --> 08:31.599
This good?

08:31.761 --> 08:35.186
That's perfect. Put that in one of
those little baggies over there.

08:43.231 --> 08:44.904
- Huh.
- "Huh," what?

08:46.026 --> 08:48.028
His eye is normal.

08:48.862 --> 08:49.909
Come take a look.

08:51.906 --> 08:54.000
No defiant pupil.

08:54.159 --> 08:56.207
That doesn't make any sense.

08:56.369 --> 08:58.087
If he was exposed
to the Mother Cell,

08:58.246 --> 09:00.374
- his pupil should be...
- All big and scary.

09:01.708 --> 09:04.632
Yeah. It should be.

09:04.794 --> 09:07.513
WOMAN [IN FRENCH]:

09:07.672 --> 09:09.094
MAN 1 [IN FRENCH]:

09:09.257 --> 09:11.601
WOMAN:

09:11.760 --> 09:14.809
MAN 12

09:19.392 --> 09:21.190
I think you're wrong.

09:21.728 --> 09:23.401
You understand what
tney've been saying?

09:23.563 --> 09:25.443
- Enough of it.
MAN 2 [IN ENGLISH]: And you are?

09:26.316 --> 09:27.989
[IN FRENCH]

09:28.151 --> 09:30.199
MAN 2: And, uh,
what are you thinking?

09:30.361 --> 09:31.453
Why is he wrong?

09:31.613 --> 09:34.036
Look, these aren't
necessarily normal bears.

09:34.199 --> 09:37.203
Exactly what kind
of bears are they?

09:37.368 --> 09:38.808
What do you mean,
they aren't normal?

09:40.038 --> 09:41.223
JACKSON: I don't know for sure.

09:41.247 --> 09:45.002
But, uh, look, they won't necessarily
be acting like you'd expect them to.

09:46.127 --> 09:49.222
And like she said,
bears of a sleuth stick together.

09:49.380 --> 09:52.224
So if one entered the city,
most likely the others will too.

09:52.383 --> 09:54.932
Perhaps they are
traveling underground?

09:55.095 --> 09:57.439
The sewers, tunnels,
the Catacombs?

09:57.597 --> 09:59.349
And that's why they
haven't been spotted.

09:59.516 --> 10:01.860
From what we've already seen,

10:02.018 --> 10:05.272
these bears,
they're unfazed by people.

10:05.438 --> 10:07.361
So if they want food
before they hibernate,

10:07.524 --> 10:10.448
they're gonna feed on
whatever's available.

10:10.610 --> 10:13.534
There are more than
300 miles of sewers

10:13.696 --> 10:15.915
and tunnels that
run under Paris.

10:18.201 --> 10:21.375
I suppose we'd
better get searching.

10:22.747 --> 10:24.090
That was perfect.

10:24.249 --> 10:27.628
You motivated them, maybe got them
looking in the right direction.

10:27.794 --> 10:28.966
Chloe.

10:30.964 --> 10:32.932
[BOTH SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

10:37.971 --> 10:41.316
Uh, Jean-Michel
Lion, Jackson Oz.

10:41.474 --> 10:42.566
- Hey.
- Hello.

10:42.934 --> 10:46.313
Jean-I\/Iichel is
a civil engineer.

10:46.479 --> 10:48.527
I did not know you were back.

10:48.690 --> 10:50.909
Your sister said you left town.

10:51.067 --> 10:52.569
I'm just here for a few days.

10:54.154 --> 10:55.827
And why are the
Americans interested

10:55.989 --> 10:58.083
in a pack of missing
French bears?

10:58.741 --> 11:00.414
- I'm sorry, I can't tell you.
- Ah.

11:00.577 --> 11:04.457
Secret affairs I understand,
but, uh, heh, bears?

11:06.249 --> 11:08.798
If I could tell you, I would.
But I can't.

11:09.502 --> 11:10.970
Okay.

11:11.129 --> 11:14.349
If I get any leads on where they may
be, I'll call you straightaway.

11:14.507 --> 11:15.599
Thank you.

11:16.759 --> 11:18.636
[IN FRENCH]

11:25.268 --> 11:27.737
[IN FRENCH]

11:32.692 --> 11:35.741
So that's him, huh?
The ex-fiancé.

11:35.904 --> 11:37.747
[IN ENGLISH] That's him.

11:39.324 --> 11:42.669
So there's two beds
in the guest bedroom.

11:42.827 --> 11:45.626
And the sofa opens up
into a bed as well.

11:45.788 --> 11:49.258
The most important question
is: Where is the wine?

11:49.417 --> 11:51.590
I hear you French are
very famous for it.

11:51.753 --> 11:54.302
In the kitchen. Help yourself.

11:55.548 --> 11:58.722
So l... No defiant pupil?
What does that mean?

11:59.802 --> 12:00.894
I don't know yet.

12:01.179 --> 12:02.419
But it doesn't necessarily mean

12:02.555 --> 12:04.478
that the bear wasn't
affected by the Mother Cell.

12:05.308 --> 12:08.278
Blood labs should be back
in a couple of hours.

12:08.436 --> 12:12.737
But why else would a bear be
hibernating in the middle of summer?

12:13.441 --> 12:15.535
There are two types of
hibernation, okay?

12:15.693 --> 12:17.240
One is what we
normally think of:

12:17.403 --> 12:19.576
Yogi Bear goes into a
deep suspended animation

12:19.739 --> 12:22.162
to survive a winter
of scarce resources.

12:22.325 --> 12:26.125
The other is when an animal
falls temporarily dormant,

12:26.287 --> 12:29.917
so that resources can be
biologically redirected.

12:30.083 --> 12:31.835
What does that
mean, "redirected"?

12:32.001 --> 12:36.802
Like a caterpillar
turning into a butterfly,

12:36.965 --> 12:40.310
or when little kids sleep so
deeply when they're growing.

12:41.761 --> 12:45.231
So you mean you think
that the bear's changing?

12:46.474 --> 12:47.691
I think it's possible.

12:48.851 --> 12:50.728
The question is,

12:50.895 --> 12:52.613
into what?

13:16.462 --> 13:17.930
[CELL PHONE CHIMES]

13:28.349 --> 13:29.817
- Hey. JACKSON: Hey.

13:29.976 --> 13:31.978
Dinner's almost ready.

13:32.145 --> 13:34.068
- Cool.
- And we should, uh, probably

13:34.230 --> 13:36.107
talk about Mitch's new
theory about the bears.

13:36.274 --> 13:39.369
Yes. Delavane wants to see me.

13:39.527 --> 13:41.950
I'll be back as soon as I can.

13:50.121 --> 13:52.670
Jamie, vino?

13:52.957 --> 13:54.379
Thank you.

13:56.586 --> 13:59.760
But it's "Nancy." I should
get used to saying it.

14:01.507 --> 14:04.477
As far as names go,
it's not so bad.

14:06.137 --> 14:07.935
It was my mother's.

14:08.348 --> 14:10.726
"Armstrong" was her maiden name.

14:17.440 --> 14:18.987
Abdullah Balogun.

14:19.150 --> 14:20.493
Sorry?

14:21.861 --> 14:24.330
I had another name once too.

14:25.365 --> 14:27.663
When I was 13 years old,

14:27.825 --> 14:29.577
my parents were
killed in a raid.

14:30.578 --> 14:33.206
Me and my little brothers
were taken in by the rebels.

14:33.664 --> 14:35.541
The United Republic Army.

14:35.708 --> 14:37.961
Malik and Kalim.

14:38.878 --> 14:40.095
The rebels fed us

14:40.254 --> 14:42.473
and gave us shelter.

14:42.632 --> 14:46.353
But then a few days later,
I was made to undertake a...

14:46.511 --> 14:47.808
initiation.

14:47.970 --> 14:49.972
[MEN YEl_l_lNG]

14:51.474 --> 14:54.148
It was their way of breaking me.

14:54.977 --> 14:56.900
Forcing me to...

14:57.063 --> 14:59.532
prove my loyalty to them.

15:04.404 --> 15:05.451
They gave me a gun.

15:05.613 --> 15:06.693
[MAN SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

15:07.281 --> 15:08.908
And a single bullet.

15:10.076 --> 15:11.123
And told me...

15:12.537 --> 15:14.460
that I must choose...

15:15.581 --> 15:19.256
which of my two
brothers I should kill.

15:20.503 --> 15:22.346
And I was told...

15:22.797 --> 15:25.175
that if I did not
shoot one of them,

15:25.341 --> 15:26.809
then they would both be killed.

15:29.470 --> 15:31.689
I looked into the eyes
of my baby brothers.

15:31.848 --> 15:35.443
So sweet, so gentle.

15:35.601 --> 15:39.731
And I knew from that moment
that they were both condemned.

15:42.859 --> 15:45.408
You see, one of them would die,

15:46.112 --> 15:47.910
but the other,

15:48.072 --> 15:49.619
like me,

15:50.741 --> 15:52.334
would be turned into an animal.

15:54.203 --> 15:56.376
[INHALES SHARPLY]

15:57.957 --> 15:59.880
So I made the only
decision I could.

16:01.002 --> 16:03.255
I chose neither.

16:08.176 --> 16:10.429
And I sent them both
to a better place.

16:11.220 --> 16:12.938
[GUNSHOTS]

16:19.854 --> 16:21.447
Five years later,

16:21.606 --> 16:26.077
I escaped from the army and
changed my name to Abraham.

16:27.945 --> 16:30.414
And I went somewhere
they would never find me.

16:30.573 --> 16:34.623
And even though I knew I did
the right thing for my brothers,

16:35.119 --> 16:38.464
I've been spending my whole life
trying to make up for my choice

16:38.623 --> 16:41.718
by protecting the
people I care about.

16:42.460 --> 16:43.757
My new family.

16:48.674 --> 16:52.224
And now you are part
of that family too.

16:54.597 --> 16:55.940
Miss Nancy Armstrong.

16:59.560 --> 17:00.937
DELAVANE: Killed him?

17:01.521 --> 17:03.273
An FBI agent.

17:03.439 --> 17:06.282
A dirty FBI agent. At best.

17:06.442 --> 17:09.069
So you've just said. Who?

17:09.237 --> 17:10.910
Who killed him?

17:11.656 --> 17:13.657
I can't tell you.

17:14.325 --> 17:15.998
A member of my team.

17:16.327 --> 17:18.750
The good news is,
I've been tracking channels,

17:18.913 --> 17:20.756
and there hasn't
been any chatter.

17:20.915 --> 17:24.545
None. It's almost as if they
haven't discovered his body yet.

17:24.710 --> 17:26.053
But they will.

17:26.212 --> 17:29.637
And whether he was a real FBI
agent on the take for Reiden

17:29.799 --> 17:32.393
or posing as an FBI
agent, either case,

17:32.552 --> 17:34.554
this is now a federal matter,

17:34.720 --> 17:37.599
which means they won't stop until
they find out who killed him.

17:37.765 --> 17:40.314
Which means, eventually,
they will find us.

17:40.476 --> 17:43.400
And everything we are
doing will become public,

17:43.563 --> 17:46.191
which will make it
impossible to do our job.

17:46.357 --> 17:47.859
So, what are you saying?

17:48.025 --> 17:49.447
You want me to turn them in?

17:49.610 --> 17:52.705
I'm saying, Agent Tousignant,

17:52.863 --> 17:54.410
that you may not
have asked for it,

17:54.574 --> 17:58.420
but nothing is more important
than the task you have been given.

17:58.578 --> 18:01.331
To figure out what is happening
to the animals and how to stop it.

18:01.497 --> 18:02.623
I am doing that.

18:03.583 --> 18:05.711
As much as you may
have come to like them

18:05.876 --> 18:07.628
and want to protect them,

18:07.795 --> 18:09.513
none of the people on your team

18:09.672 --> 18:13.518
are more important than your
ability to complete that task.

18:15.136 --> 18:18.481
Do you understand
what I'm saying?

18:20.600 --> 18:21.692
Yes, sir.

18:30.901 --> 18:32.421
How do we get past the
facial recognition?

18:32.445 --> 18:33.492
No problem at all.

18:33.654 --> 18:35.873
All we need is an employee
with top-level access.

18:36.032 --> 18:37.909
Right, because why
would that be a problem?

18:38.075 --> 18:39.122
CHLOE: Hey.

18:39.452 --> 18:40.544
