every penny of their finances,

19:46.394 --> 19:48.362
so if there's a
payoff to Ben Shafer,

19:48.521 --> 19:50.364
it'll be in their
accounting records.

19:50.523 --> 19:53.948
We just access the finances
and follow the paper trail.

19:54.110 --> 19:56.033
Presuming that he
used his real name.

19:56.654 --> 19:59.123
Agreed. It's not necessarily
going to be easy,

19:59.281 --> 20:01.329
but there's always something.

20:01.492 --> 20:04.041
Uh, money that moves from
one account to another.

20:04.203 --> 20:06.581
- Numbers that don't add up.
- A pattern.

20:06.747 --> 20:08.044
That's your specialty, right?

20:08.207 --> 20:10.209
Recognizing patterns.

20:10.376 --> 20:12.470
Okay, you say

20:12.628 --> 20:15.256
once we access their finances.

20:15.423 --> 20:17.704
- How are we gonna do that?
JACKSON: That's the cool part.

20:17.842 --> 20:19.810
See, as far as we can tell,

20:19.969 --> 20:23.940
all top-level Reiden executives have
access to their computer network.

20:24.265 --> 20:26.108
But the system
doesn't use passwords.

20:26.267 --> 20:27.564
It uses facial recognition.

20:27.727 --> 20:30.480
So we just need to locate
an executive with access

20:30.646 --> 20:32.569
and then trick their
system into thinking

20:32.732 --> 20:34.234
they're signing
into their account.

20:34.400 --> 20:36.619
